        <h3>Understanding Radon Levels</h3>
        <div style="background:#f8f9fa;padding:20px;border-radius:10px;margin:20px 0;">
          <h4>Radon Level Guidelines:</h4>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Below 2.0 pCi/L:</strong> Low risk, no action needed</li>
            <li><strong>2.0 – 4.0 pCi/L:</strong> Consider mitigation, especially for long-term exposure</li>
            <li><strong>4.0 – 8.0 pCi/L:</strong> Mitigation recommended</li>
            <li><strong>Above 8.0 pCi/L:</strong> Immediate mitigation strongly recommended</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <h3>Why Choose Professional Testing?</h3>
        <p>While DIY test kits are available, professional testing offers several advantages:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>More accurate continuous monitoring equipment</li>
          <li>Proper placement and environmental controls</li>
          <li>Immediate results and expert interpretation</li>
          <li>Compliance with real estate transaction requirements</li>
          <li>Detailed reporting for insurance and mitigation planning</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>When to Test</h3>
        <p>The EPA recommends testing your home:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Every 2 years as part of routine home maintenance</li>
          <li>Before buying or selling a home</li>
          <li>After any structural changes to your home</li>
          <li>If you're finishing a basement or lower level</li>
          <li>After installing a radon mitigation system (post-mitigation testing)</li>
        </ul>

